      "writtenOn": "2026-06-09T22:45:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "To be precise about what the patch actually changes:\n\nBOOST_ASIO_HAS_IO_URING stays set. boost::asio::random_access_file\u0027s io_uring_file_service is gated on HAS_IO_URING alone (not on HAS_IO_URING_AS_DEFAULT), so every sysfs read in HwmonTempSensor / PSUSensor / SMBPBI / PSUEvent / TachSensor continues through io_uring kworkers. The kernel still does the I2C work asynchronously.\n\nWhat DISABLE_EPOLL additionally forces into io_uring beyond file I/O:\n - D-Bus sockets (PropertiesChanged, method dispatch)\n - steady_timer (every poll cycle in every sensor)\n - posix::stream_descriptor (CPUSensor\u0027s read fd)\n\nThose don\u0027t benefit from io_uring\u0027s offload model - a timer firing isn\u0027t I/O-bound, an inbound D-Bus message isn\u0027t slow. epoll handles them well. Routing them through io_uring puts a steady stream of trivial completions through kworkers, which is what\u0027s pegging iowait.\n\nSo the patch is scoping io_uring usage to file I/O instead of forcing it on everything. CPUSensor going back to the epoll path is what 46918 originally documented before DISABLE_EPOLL was added; #19 is the regression caused by that addition.\n\nMeasured behavior on AST2600 (host off, all daemons running, 5s window):\n                                BEFORE              AFTER\n top                            99% io              0% io / 83% idle\n iowait ticks/s                 +193/s              0\n idle ticks/s                   0 (frozen)          +170/s\n i2c bus 4 IRQ rate             +328/s              +377/s     (same)\n\ni2c IRQ rate unchanged - same read frequency, same async behavior. D-Bus PropertiesChanged delivered at the unchanged 500ms per-sensor cadence in my test.\n\nOf course, it needs to be tested on heavy load with lots of sensor connections so it\u0027s the reason why I left a note in the commit message.",
