      "writtenOn": "2026-06-09T22:45:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "1. Agree in general on \"iowait is a feature\". The specific situation: with DISABLE_EPOLL set, every dbus-sensors event (sockets, timers, files) is dispatched through io_uring, and lightweight events get punted to kernel workers that sit in io_schedule() while the user io_context thread is already busy processing the next callback. Kernel reports the kworker waits as iowait; the daemon itself is not blocked. The 99% iowait is therefore \"kworkers exist,\" not \"I/O is bottlenecking the BMC.\"\n\n2. From Boost\u0027s config.hpp:\n\n```\n  // Linux: io_uring is used instead of epoll.\n  #if !defined(BOOST_ASIO_HAS_IO_URING_AS_DEFAULT)\n  # if !defined(BOOST_ASIO_HAS_EPOLL) \u0026\u0026 defined(BOOST_ASIO_HAS_IO_URING)\n  #  define BOOST_ASIO_HAS_IO_URING_AS_DEFAULT 1\n  # endif\n  #endif\n```\n\nHAS_IO_URING_AS_DEFAULT is auto-set only when EPOLL is disabled AND IO_URING is still enabled. So file I/O is not switching to blocking calls. As long as BOOST_ASIO_HAS_IO_URING is kept, random_access_file compiles unconditionally on io_uring whenever that macro is defined.",
      "parentUuid": "a24d651e_ffdc7379",
      "revId": "9dd9bcdd4021fd59e23a75813efe95ac451d4f60",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
